      <h2>To Begin - Launching Point</h2>
      <h3>Course Homepage</h3>
      <p>The online student cannot size up the situation in the same manner as a
        student seated in a physical lecture hall or classroom. But first
        impressions, whether generated in person or online, can be long lasting.
        The intent of course homepage is to whet student's appetite. This is the
        opportunity to stimulate interest, while also sending messages about
        expectations. </p>
      <p>By using the homepage to introduce the purpose and significance of a
        course and convey the mindset of the lecturer to the reader,<span style="color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; display: inline !important; float: none;">
          the tone for the entire course can be set. This, according to Lang, </span>“condition(s)
        student attitudes toward the entire course, the effort they are willing
        to put into it, and the relationship they will have with you and their
        peers throughout the semester”. </p>
      <p>At a glance, the homepage should convey the “shape” of the course and
        how this fits within student's overall educational experience. Once
        students have completed reading through the page, they should be
        convinced about the competence of the lecturer, be able to predict the
        structure of class and sequence of activities, and know what is required
        of them.</p>
